This paper deals with the achievable communication rates of a transmission system for the optical fiber channel, which involves modulation of parameters of the scattering domain by the information bits. This involves the use of information theory and perturbation theory to analyze the influence of various factors on the achievable rates. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper deals with the use of soliton-based transmission systems, which are relevant to the sub-categories cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.PL (Programming Languages). The paper also discusses the use of inverse scattering transform and direct spectral transform, which are relevant to the sub-category cs.SI (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper discusses the limitations of the system due to time of arrival jitter, which is relevant to the sub-category cs.OH (Other Computer Science).
